mts.s: We will accomplish this by building sensors that use arduinos and a website that will help display information to the people who visit the Technology Garden. Other goals involve more sensors to see how much we can track and help in the care for the plants.

1.0 Introduction/Background

We are Team Overkill! and our goal for the project is to improve the care of the plants inside the Technology Garden. It is difficult to tell if the plants have been watered, or over-watered. It is clear from visiting the place that there is a problem by reading the journal, and the bulletin board. This room has been operational since 2007 and by judging how many old pots we found of dead plants it looks like it could use some improvements in the way they handle things.

2.0 Business Objective

We will accomplish help the plants by building sensors that use arduinos and collect data about the plants. First finding out about moisture levels and then displaying this information in a useful way. By building a website that collects the data from the sensors we will be able to alert the people in the room how the plants are doing. We also had the idea of creating a machine that could water the plants automatically.

3.0 Current Situation and Problem/Opportunity Statement

Currently the Technology Garden does not use sensors, but has people use their best judgement about the plants. Also people have entered the room and right away gone straight to work on their laptop without thinking about watering the plants. It seems that people are confused about what to do in the Tech Garden and whose job it is to take care of the plants. We would like to clear it up by using sensors to display information to people and make them aware, or build something that will automatically water the plants.

4.0 Critical Assumption and Constraints

A constraint is that we must work inside the Technology Garden. The Technology Garden is located in Donald Bren Hall, which locks its doors at 6pm and isn’t open on weekends. It is possible to still work inside Donald Bren Hall if you are inside before 6pm, but once you leave there is no getting back in. Another solution for getting access to Donald Bren Hall is to get a key. Sometimes the Technology Garden is full of people, who use it as a study area, so it is a public place that we must share. It is possible we could ask them to leave or if they wouldn’t mind us working in there with them. The Technology Garden is sometimes locked even when Donald Bren Hall is open. We must find out who opens the door and either ask them to open it for us or maybe get a key of our own. Time constraints in our schedule are another problem where our entire group can only meet Tuesday, Thursday, and Friday at 7pm.

6.0 Preliminary Project Requirements

We will need Arduinos, and other things to build the sensor. A domain for the website. The use of the Technology Garden and all it’s contents including the plants, the monitor, and anything else we find use for. We may need a key or a quick way to access the Donald Bren Hall or the Technology Garden if they are locked.

7.0 Budget Estimate and Financial Analysis

There is no budget? You will save money on having to buy new plants that replace the dead ones.

8.0 Schedule Estimate

We must finish the project by March 13 or 15. We have to give a presentation one of those days so I’m assuming that is when it is due. There are several milestones that must be met that can’t be changed. Scope Statement and Work Breakdown Structure due February 4. Gantt Chart for the Project due February 13. Cost, Quality and Risk Management due 22. Building the sensor, the website and other parts are pretty flexible.

9.0  Potential Risks

A potential risk is not being able to complete the project. It is possible that the sensor doesn’t get built, which is what the entire project rides on. We haven’t decided what, or how many types of sensors there are going to be so there is still some uncertainty about those. We don’t know if our change to the Technology Garden will be accepted. Even if it does get accepted we don’t know if the project will actually affect the people inside it without many hours of observation, or doing an ethnography.

1.0 Introduction/Background

We are Team Overkill! Our project’s goal simple. We will use technology to increase the ease of caring for the plants of the Technology Garden. From our visits to the Technology Garden, we have discovered the room contains by many old pots and dead plants. It is clear that there has been no real maintenance of the room since the original project ended. Where others would see an empty room filled with dying plants, we see an opportunity--one to take what the previous project did in 2007, and improve upon it further. We are not alone in this opinion--many students, and even some non-students, find the state of the garden unacceptable. Their angry posts to the garden’s post board makes it clear--the garden needs to be improved, and we are the right people for the job, because we understand these problems.
2.0 Business Objective

We will accomplish our goal of improving the quality of the plants by building moisture sensors that will be placed in flower pots around the Technology Garden. The information output by each sensor will be read by the Arduino (a prototyping platform) and recorded into a database. This database will then display the data recorded from the sensors via a website. The website will assist visitors to the Technology Garden by giving them information about the plants and suggesting when the plants should be watered. The system will include the option to use this information to automatically water the plants. We will determine whether or not this feature is needed--making visitors water the plants is closer to the true goal of the technology garden, as far as we are concerned.
3.0 Current Situation and Problem/Opportunity Statement

Currently the Technology Garden no longer uses any form of sensors and has become more of a traditional garden. This forces people to use their best judgement about watering the plants. In addition, it seems unclear who is in charge of taking care of the plants. We want to improve this dismal situation. We will use sensors to display critical watering-related data to visitors to the Technology Garden. We will hopefully attempt to make the visitors water the plants when needed, and when visitors are not available, we will provide an optional automatic watering system to handle the work.
4.0 Critical Assumptions and Constraints

Some of the assumptions we have are as follows:
That we can access the Technology Garden.
That the Arduino can contact the internet from inside that room.
That the Arduino can interface with the website we create.
That the room’s purpose will not be completely changed by the building staff before our project is over.
That we are allowed to modify parts of the Technology Garden in the name of making it less abandoned/empty.
That the equipment in the Technology Garden is not stolen or moved away from where we can access it.
That we are not displaced by another group or a previous group doing the same thing we are trying to do now.

A constraint is that we must work inside the Technology Garden. The Technology Garden is located in Donald Bren Hall, which locks its doors at 6pm and isn’t open on weekends. It is possible to still work inside Donald Bren Hall if you are inside before 6pm, but once you leave there is no getting back in. Another solution for getting access to Donald Bren Hall is to get a key. However, the Technology Garden is sometimes locked even when Donald Bren Hall is open. We must find out who opens the door and either ask them to open it for us or maybe get a key of our own.

Sometimes the Technology Garden is full of people who use it as a study area, so it is a public place that we must share. It is possible we could ask them to leave or if they wouldn’t mind us working in there with them, but there is still a possibility of running into a problem.

Time constraints in our schedule are another problem where our entire group can only meet Tuesday, Thursday, and Friday at 7pm.
5.0 Analysis of Options and Recommendation

There are 4 options for addressing this opportunity:

1. Do nothing. The Technology garden is still being maintained and the plants that remain will probably survive. However, there is still a high chance of visitors leaving angry posts on the bulletin board complaining about the quality of the garden. This option is not being taken because it fails to address the underlying problem and the plants at the current rate will all die off, leaving the room completely barren if nothing changes.

2. Plant-link is a gardening management system which allows people to “listen to their plants”. We could use Plant-Link--except it is not fully finished. It allows the functionality to monitor plants, though it is more limited than Parrot Flower--and also highly expensive. It only monitors the water levels meaning that everything else still has to be inputted in manually. Our device can be customized to fit our situation by us for almost no money at all--much better than paying for the Plant-Link system and team to do the work for us because relying on their system could potentially limit customization for specific situation and use.

3. Use Parrot flower. This device is an all-in-one machine that uses the Cloud to send data to smartphones and warn the user on lack of water, temperature issues, sunlight issues and soil issues. Problem: System is not out yet and will not be ready in time for us to use. It may also be too expensive. Since the system has not yet been finalized--it may not even be completed at all. However, if the system was to be actually completed earlier than the website suggests, it could possibly do all of the work for us, and rather easily. We will consider this when we are developing our own project--which is easier, cheaper, and quicker than waiting for this “Parrot Flower”.

4. Use the Arduino Sensors we have. We have chosen this solution, because we already have the parts. It costs next to nothing (less than $100) to expand the system. Compatible parts have also been found in the Technology Garden. The previous project in the Technology Garden also used similar parts. Therefore, our project, combined with our website, allows us to execute the plan with low cost and usage of skills we already have. Plus, we have already tested the Arduino and determined that it works, and that it is usable. 
6.0 Preliminary Project Requirements

We will need Arduinos and other things to build the sensor. A domain for the website. The use of the Technology Garden and all it’s contents including the plants, the monitor, and anything else we find use for. We may need a key or a quick way to access the Donald Bren Hall or the Technology Garden if they are locked.

Specifically:
The system will need to accurately measure plant’s conditions.
The recorded information must be presented on the website in an aesthetically pleasing manner.
The Technology Garden must become more of an interesting and an interactive place to be so more people will come to visit, and in doing so will help to maintain it more.
The system must compel those who see it to water the plants.
7.0 Budget Estimate and Financial Analysis

The Budget for our project will be $50-100. We have many parts on hand like the Arduino, and basic electrical components like wire, leds resistors and capacitors, but will require more plants, more probes and an ethernet shield for the arduino in order to complete the project. Otherwise, pre-existing programs and tools that do not cost any further money shall be used.
8.0 Schedule Estimate

We must finish the project by March 13 or 15, so that we can give our Final Presentation on it in time for the end of the Quarter. There are several milestones that must be met that can’t be changed, so we will follow those for our schedule. Our Scope Statement and Work Breakdown Structure is due February 4. Then, our Gantt Chart for the Project is due February 13. Finally, our Cost, Quality and Risk Management paper is due 22. Outside of that, building the sensor, the website and other parts are pretty flexible. Just to be safe, though, we have already gotten the sensor working and are already beginning work on the website, and will most likely have it underway before our Gantt Chart is due.
9.0  Potential Risks

A potential risk is not being able to complete the project. Something adverse could happen to prevent proper website-Arduino integration. The Technology Garden could end up being repurposed, excluding us from being able to use it. Visitors to the room could potentially steal our equipment. We could be forbidden from working on the room, or the original project staff could return and end up displacing us from the room after deciding to do the work themselves. We haven’t decided what, or how many types of sensors there are going to be so there is still some uncertainty about those. We don’t know if our change to the Technology Garden will be accepted. Even if it does get accepted we don’t know if the project will actually affect the people inside it without many hours of observation, or doing an ethnography.
